30 PART II. PHARMACY SERVICES ADMINISTRATIVE ORGANIZATIONS
31 TRANSPARENCY AND FREEDOM OF CONTRACT
32 SECTION 2.1. Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
33 Article to read:
34 "Article 56B.
35 "Pharmacy Services Administrative Organizations.
36 "§ 58-56B-1. Definitions.
37 The following definitions apply in this Article:
38 (1) Reserved for future codification purposes.
39 (2) Independent pharmacy. – As defined in G.S. 58-51-37.
40 (3) Insured. – An individual covered by a health benefit plan.
41 (4) Pharmacy. – As defined in G.S. 58-51-37.
42 (5) Pharmacy benefits manager or PBM. – As defined in G.S. 58-56A-1.
43 (6) Pharmacy services administrative organization or PSAO. – An entity
44 operating within this State that contracts with one or more independent
45 pharmacies to conduct business with third-party payers on behalf of the
46 independent pharmacy or pharmacies to provide administrative services to the
47 independent pharmacy or pharmacies and to negotiate and enter into contracts
48 with third-party payers or PBMs on behalf of the independent pharmacy or
49 pharmacies. Administrative services provided on behalf of one or more
50 independent pharmacies may include one or more of the following:
51 a. Assistance with claims.
Page 4 Senate Bill 479-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. Assistance with audits.
2 c. Centralized payment.
3 d. Certification in specialized care programs.
4 e. Compliance support.
5 f. Setting flat fees for generic drugs.
6 g. Assistance with store layout.
7 h. Inventory management.
8 i. Marketing support.
9 j. Management and analysis of payment and drug dispensing data.
10 k. Provision of services for retail cash cards.
11 (7) PSAO-pharmacy contract. – A contractual agreement between a PSAO and
12 an independent pharmacy under which a PSAO agrees to negotiate with PBMs
13 or third-party payers or both on behalf of an independent pharmacy. A
14 PSAO-pharmacy contract may contain an agreement that the PSAO will
15 provide other services to the independent pharmacy in addition to negotiation
16 with PBMs or third-party payers.
17 (8) Reserved for future codification purposes.
18 (9) Wholesale distributor. – As defined in G.S. 106-145.2.
19 "§ 58-56B-5. Regulation of PSAOs by Department.
20 (a) Licensure Requirement. – No pharmacy services administrative organization that
21 negotiates with PBMs, third-party payers, or both on behalf of any pharmacy in this State shall
22 operate without obtaining a license from the Department.
23 (b) Application. – The Commissioner shall develop an application for licensure as a
24 pharmacy services administrative organization and may charge an initial application fee of two
25 hundred dollars ($200.00) and an annual renewal fee of one hundred fifty dollars ($150.00). The
26 application form must collect at least the following information:
27 (1) The name, address, and telephone contact number of the PSAO.
28 (2) The name and address of the PSAO's agent for service of process in this State.
29 (3) The name and address of each individual with management or control over
30 the PSAO.
31 (4) The name and address of each individual or entity with a beneficial ownership
32 interest in the PSAO.
33 (5) Either (i) a signed statement that, to the best of the applicant's knowledge, no
34 officer with management or control of the PSAO has been convicted of a
35 felony or has violated any requirement of State or federal law applicable to
36 pharmacy services administration, pharmacy benefits management, or
37 pharmacy services or (ii) a description of any felony or any violation of any
38 requirement of State or federal law applicable to pharmacy services
39 administration, pharmacy benefits management, or pharmacy services
40 committed by any officer with management or control of the pharmacy
41 benefits manager.
42 (c) Application Modifications. – Unless otherwise provided for in this Article, an
43 applicant or a PSAO that is licensed to conduct business in the State shall file a notice describing
44 any material modification of the information required to be contained in the licensure application
45 under this section.
46 (d) Report and Disclose Requirements of Licensees. – Information contained in a report
47 or disclosure required to be submitted to the Department by a PSAO under this Article shall not
48 reveal any personally identifiable information of any insured. Information contained in this report
49 is not considered a public record under Chapter 132 of the General Statutes or under
50 G.S. 58-2-100 and is confidential and privileged.
51 "§ 58-56B-10. Disclosure of ownership requirements.
Senate Bill 479-Fourth Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) To the Department. – Prior to licensure under this Article and within 10 calendar days
2 of any material change to that disclosure, each PSAO shall provide a written disclosure of
3 ownership to the Department.
4 (b) To Independent Pharmacies, PBMs, and Third-Party Payers. – Prior to entering into
5 a contract with an independent pharmacy, PBM, or third-party payer, a PSAO shall provide the
6 pharmacy, PBM, or third-party payer a written disclosure of ownership or control in order to
7 assist the pharmacy, PBM, or third-party payer in making an informed decision regarding the
8 relationship with the PSAO and the pharmacy, including the PSAO's relationship with any
9 independent pharmacy on behalf of which the PSAO is negotiating.
10 (c) Content of Required Disclosures. – A disclosure of ownership required under this
11 section shall include the extent of any ownership or control of the PSAO by any parent company,
12 subsidiary, or other organization that does any of the following:
13 (1) Provides pharmacy services or support.
14 (2) Provides prescription drugs or drug services.
15 (3) Manufactures, sells, or distributes prescription drugs, biological products, or
16 medical devices.
17 (d) Updates to Required Disclosure. – If there is any material change in ownership or
18 control of a PSAO relating to any disclosure required under this section, then a PSAO shall notify
19 the Department and all relevant independent pharmacies, PBMs, and third-party payers of this
20 change within 10 calendar days of the change.
21 "§ 58-56B-15. Contract requirements.
22 (a) Negotiated Terms. – A PSAO-pharmacy contract shall include a requirement that the
23 PSAO provide to the pharmacy a copy of any contract, amendment, payment schedule, or
24 reimbursement rate within 10 calendar days after the execution of, or amendment to, a contract
25 that the PSAO has signed on behalf of the independent pharmacy.
26 (b) Updates to Required Disclosures. – A contract between a PSAO and an independent
27 pharmacy, PBM, or third-party payer shall include the requirement that the PSAO update
28 disclosures in accordance with G.S. 58-56B-10(d).
29 (c) Prohibition on Certain Purchase Requirements. – A PSAO shall not require a
30 pharmacy to purchase specific amounts of prescription drugs, whether generic or brand name, in
31 order to access discounts.
32 (d) Audits. – If a PSAO-pharmacy contract grants a PBM the right or obligation to
33 conduct audits of an independent pharmacy, then that PSAO-pharmacy contract is required to
34 contain language that permits the PBM to obtain information from the PSAO in connection with
35 the PBM's audit of that independent pharmacy.
36 (e) Timely Transmission of Remittance. – A PSAO-pharmacy contract shall provide that
37 all remittances for claims submitted to the PSAO by a PBM or third-party payer on behalf of the
38 independent pharmacy shall be passed through by the PSAO to the pharmacy within a reasonable
39 amount of time after receipt of the remittance by the PSAO from a PBM or third-party payer.
40 The reasonable amount of time required under this section shall be established in the
41 PSAO-pharmacy contract.
42 "§ 58-56B-20. Prohibition on price discrimination.
43 A PSAO shall not discriminate on the price of drugs sold to an independent pharmacy based
44 on the price of drugs purchased from a wholesale distributor of the drug.
45 "§ 58-56B-30. Ownership interests in or of the PSAO by drug manufacturers, sellers, or
46 wholesale distributors.
47 (a) Prohibitions. – A PSAO that owns or is owned by, in whole or in part, any entity that
48 manufactures, sells, or distributes prescription drugs, biological products, or medical devices
49 shall not, as a condition of entering into a PSAO-pharmacy contract, require that the independent
50 pharmacy purchase any drugs or medical devices solely from an entity with which the PSAO has
51 an ownership interest or that has an ownership in the PSAO.
Page 6 Senate Bill 479-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Disclosure Requirements. – A PSAO that owns or is owned by, in whole or in part,
2 any entity that manufactures, sells, or distributes prescription drugs, biological products, or
3 medical devices shall disclose to the Department any agreement with an independent pharmacy
4 to purchase prescription drugs, biological products, or medical devices by an independent
5 pharmacy from the PSAO or an entity with which the PSAO has an ownership interest or that
6 has an ownership in the PSAO.
7 "§ 58-56B-35. Appeals.
8 (a) Disputes. – If there is a dispute between an independent pharmacy and a PBM or
9 third-party payer, then a PSAO which has entered into a PSAO-pharmacy contract with that
10 independent pharmacy shall ensure and facilitate timely communication between the pharmacy
11 and the PBM or third-party payer.
12 (b) PSAO Contracted with an Independent Pharmacy. – If a third-party payer or a PBM
13 provides any notice or other information to a PSAO that is related to an independent pharmacy
14 with which the PSAO has entered into a PSAO-pharmacy contract, then that shall be considered
15 provision of that notice or other information to the pharmacy with which the PSAO is contracted.
16 A third-party payer or PBM shall not be required to provide notice or other information to both
17 the PSAO and the independent pharmacy with which the PSAO has entered into a
18 PSAO-pharmacy contract.
19 (c) Timeliness. – A PSAO shall forward all notices of appeals from an independent
20 pharmacy with which the PSAO has entered into a PSAO-pharmacy contract to the relevant PBM
21 or third-party payer in a timely manner.
22 (d) Denials. – If an appeal received by a PSAO from an independent pharmacy does not
23 meet the minimum requirements contained within a PSAO-pharmacy contract, then the PSAO
24 shall notify the pharmacy and provide the denial reason or reasons. The PSAO shall allow the
25 pharmacy to resubmit the appeal for review by a PBM, if applicable.
26 "§ 58-56B-40. Penalties.
27 (a) Financial Penalty. – Any PSAO that fails to comply with the provisions of this Article,
28 as determined by the Commissioner, shall pay a penalty of five hundred dollars ($500.00) per
29 day from the day the Commissioner notifies the PSAO of noncompliance until the Commissioner
30 determines the applicable provision is met.
31 (b) Impact on Licensure. – Failure to comply with this Article may be grounds for
32 revocation or nonrenewal of a license under this Article, as determined by the Commissioner.
33 (c) Unfair Trade. – A violation of any of the following provisions of this Article is an
34 unfair trade practice under Article 63 of this Chapter and under G.S. 75-1.1:
35 (1) G.S. 58-56B-10.
36 (2) G.S. 58-56B-15.
37 (3) G.S. 58-56B-20.
38 (4) G.S. 58-56B-30.
39 (5) G.S. 58-56B-35.
40 "§ 58-56B-45. Fiduciary duty.
41 A PSAO has a duty of good faith and fair dealing and a fiduciary duty to independent
42 pharmacies to avoid conflicts of interest."
43 SECTION 2.1A.(a) Article 56B of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes, as amended
44 by Section 2.1 of this act, is amended by adding a new section to read:
45 "§ 58-56B-50. Rules.
46 The Commissioner of Insurance is authorized to adopt rules, temporary or otherwise,
47 regarding the administration of this Article."
48 SECTION 2.1A.(b) No later than October 1, 2026, the Commissioner of Insurance
49 shall adopt rules necessary to implement this part of this act.
50 SECTION 2.1A.(c) This section is effective when it becomes law.
