33 PART IX. PRESCRIPTION DRUG TRANSPARENCY
34 SECTION 9.(a) Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
35 Article to read:
36 "Article 4D.
37 "Prescription Drug Transparency.
38 "§ 90-85.55. Definitions.
39 The following definitions apply in this Article:
40 (1) Interested parties. – All of the following:
41 a. State agencies that (i) purchase prescription drugs or (ii) employ
42 prescribers.
43 b. Health insurance companies.
44 c. Health care service plan providers.
45 d. Pharmacy benefits managers.
46 (2) Manufacturer. – An entity or an agent of an entity that produces, prepares,
47 propagates, compounds, processes, packages, repackages, or labels a
48 brand-name or generic drug. "Manufacturer" does not include an entity
49 engaged in the preparation and dispensing of a brand-name or generic drug
50 pursuant to a prescription.
Senate Bill 479-Fourth Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Prescriber. – Any person authorized under the laws of this State to issue a
2 prescription order.
3 (4) Prescription drug. – Defined in G.S. 90-85.3.
4 (5) Prescription order. – Defined in G.S. 90-85.3.
5 (6) Price. – The wholesale acquisition cost as defined in 42 U.S.C. §
6 1395w-3a(c)(6)(B).
7 (7) Secretary. – The Secretary of the Department of Health and Human Services.
8 "§ 90-85.56. Required notifications and disclosures.
9 (a) Price Increases. – By January 31 of each year, a manufacturer shall notify all
10 interested parties of each increase in price of fifteen percent (15%) or greater that occurred in the
11 prior calendar year for a prescription drug with a price of one hundred dollars ($100.00) or more
12 for a 30-day supply. The manufacturer shall disclose all of the following to interested parties for
13 each drug price increase noticed for the prior calendar year under this subsection:
14 (1) The date and price of acquisition of the drug, if it was not developed by the
15 manufacturer.
16 (2) A schedule of price increases for the drug for the five years prior to the
17 calendar year for which the drug price increase was required to be noticed
18 under this subsection.
19 (b) New Products. – A manufacturer shall notify all interested parties of the price of any
20 new prescription drug within three days after it is made available for purchase in this State.
21 Within 30 days after the notification required by this subsection, the manufacturer shall disclose
22 to interested parties the date and price of acquisition of the drug if it was not developed by the
23 manufacturer.
24 (c) Satisfaction of Obligations. – A manufacturer's obligations under this section shall be
25 fully satisfied by the submission of information and data that a manufacturer includes in its
26 annual consolidated report on Securities and Exchange Commission Form 10-K or any other
27 public disclosure.
28 (d) Information is Not Public Record. – Information provided to the Secretary or an
29 interested party pursuant to this section shall, except to the extent it is already in the public
30 domain, be considered trade secret under Article 24 of Chapter 66 of the General Statutes,
31 confidential, exempt from public inspection and copying under Chapter 132 of the General
32 Statutes, and shall not be disclosed directly or indirectly. The Secretary, interested parties, and
33 their agents shall not publish or otherwise disclose any information that would allow for the
34 identification of an individual drug, therapeutic class of drugs, or manufacturer, that would reveal
35 the prices of any drug or therapeutic class of drugs, or that has the potential to compromise the
36 financial, competitive, or proprietary nature of any information submitted by the manufacturer
37 pursuant to this section. The Secretary and interested parties shall impose the confidentiality
38 protections of this section on any downstream third party that may receive or otherwise have
39 access to this information.
40 "§ 90-85.57. Penalty for failure to report.
41 The Secretary shall assess a civil penalty against any manufacturer failing to report the
42 information required by this Article. The amount of the penalty shall not exceed one thousand
43 dollars ($1,000) for each day the manufacturer fails to submit the required information. The clear
44 proceeds of any civil penalties assessed pursuant to this section shall be remitted to the Civil
45 Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2. Chapter 150B of the General
46 Statutes applies to proceedings for the assessment of civil penalties under this section.
47 "§ 90-85.58. Report and data collection by the Secretary; public portal.
48 (a) Plan for Implementation. – The Secretary shall develop a plan to collect data from
49 manufacturers pursuant to G.S. 90-85.56 to provide transparency and accountability for
50 prescription drug pricing. The Secretary shall consult with other state and national agencies and
Page 18 Senate Bill 479-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 nonprofit organizations to determine how to implement this data collection directive but shall not
2 disclose any confidential, proprietary, or trade secret information.
3 (b) Public Portal. – The Secretary shall create an online portal to provide the public with
4 access to the notifications, reports, and other disclosures required by this Article.
5 (c) Annual Report. – Beginning January 1, 2027, and annually thereafter, the Secretary
6 shall report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services the
7 following information with respect to prescription drugs sold in this State:
8 (1) The 25 drugs prescribed most frequently in the State.
9 (2) The 25 most costly drugs based on the total amount spent on those drugs by
10 consumers in this State.
11 (3) The 25 drugs with the greatest percentage cost increases during the prior
12 calendar year.
13 (4) The 10 manufacturers with the greatest average percentage cost increase for
14 the prior calendar year for all drugs sold by that manufacturer in the State."
15 SECTION 9.(b) This Part is effective when it becomes law.
16
17 PART X. PHARMACY REPORTING REQUIREMENTS
18 SECTION 10. Article 4A of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by
19 adding a new section to read:
20 "§ 90-85.42. Board of Pharmacy reporting.
21 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
22 (1) Large retail pharmacy. – More than 25 pharmacies in common ownership.
23 (2) Small retail pharmacy. – Twenty-five or fewer pharmacies in common
24 ownership.
25 (b) Reporting Requirements. – No later than October 1 of each year, the Board shall
26 report the following information to the Department of Insurance and the Joint Legislative
27 Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services:
28 (1) The current number of licensed pharmacies in the State.
29 (2) The number of small retail pharmacies that have opened in the preceding five
30 years.
31 (3) The number of large retail pharmacies that have opened in the preceding five
32 years.
33 (4) The number of small retail pharmacies that have closed in the preceding five
34 years.
35 (5) The number of large retail pharmacies that have closed in the preceding five
36 years."
37
38 PART XI. RFP CHANGES
39 SECTION 11.(a) Article 3B of Chapter 135 of the General Statutes is amended by
40 adding a new section to read:
41 "§ 135-49. Pharmacy benefits manager contracts.
42 The Executive Administrator shall consider incorporating the following items into a request
43 for proposal for a pharmacy benefits manager for the Plan:
44 (1) Allowing the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to provide a monetary
45 advantage to pharmacies in North Carolina neighborhoods, communities, and
46 counties that are underserved by pharmacies.
47 (2) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to annually report all of the
48 information required in G.S. 58-56A-22 to the State Treasurer, Commissioner
49 of Insurance, and Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and
50 Human Services no later than May 1 of each year.
Senate Bill 479-Fourth Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Preventing the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers from contractually
2 requiring independent pharmacies to accept reimbursement for a drug, device,
3 or pharmacy service in an amount that is less than the acquisition cost of the
4 drug, device, or pharmacy service.
5 (4) Requiring the Plan and the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to adhere to the
6 coverage requirements of G.S. 58-56A-55.
7 (5) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to act as a fiduciary in
8 accordance with G.S. 58-56A-21.
9 (6) Requiring the Plan and the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to adhere to the
10 pharmacy of choice provisions of G.S. 58-51-37.
11 (7) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to meet or exceed the
12 Medicare Part D program standards for convenient access to network
13 pharmacies under 42 C.F.R. § 423.120.
14 (8) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to reimburse affiliated and
15 non-affiliated pharmacies on the same terms.
16 (9) Adhering to the cost-sharing consumer protection provisions of
17 G.S. 58-3-182."
18 SECTION 11.(b) This Part becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
19 requests for proposals issued on or after that date.
20
21 PART XII. EFFECTIVE DATE
22 SECTION 12.1. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
23 law.
